\begin_layout Section
Synopsis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous chapter introduced 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA as a technique suitable for studies in non-perturbative QFT.
 This chapter explores the symmetry properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA using the 1PIEA and 2PIEA as specific examples.
 These cases cover all of the conceptual points required for general 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA, with mere increases in technical complexity for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>2$
\end_inset

.
 This chapter demonstrates that global symmetries are not generically preserved
 by truncations of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA.
 The causes of this can be understood in terms of the difference between
 1PI and 2PI (resp.
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PI) Ward identities.
 It can also be understood in terms of the resummation of perturbative Feynman
 diagrams: when an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA is truncated some subset of perturbative diagrams is summed to infinite
 order, but the complementary subset is left out entirely.
 The pattern of resummations does not guarantee that the cancellations between
 perturbative diagrams needed to maintain the symmetry are kept.
 In the case of scalar field theories with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{O}\left(N\right)\to\mathrm{O}\left(N-1\right)$
\end_inset

 breaking, the result is that the final 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{O}\left(N-1\right)$
\end_inset

 symmetry is maintained, but, at the Hartree-Fock level of approximation,
 the non-linearly realised 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{O}\left(N\right)/\mathrm{O}\left(N-1\right)$
\end_inset

 is lost, the Goldstone theorem is violated (the 
\begin_inset Formula $N-1$
\end_inset

 Goldstone bosons are massive), and the symmetry restoration phase transition
 is first order in contradiction with the second order transition expected
 on the basis of universality arguments.
 A similar problem arises in gauge theories, where the violation of gauge
 invariance in the 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

-loop truncation is due to the missing 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(l+1\right)$
\end_inset

-loop diagrams (see, e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "York2012,York2014"

\end_inset

 for a discussion of the gauge fixing problem).
 These results are known in the literature, but the demonstration given
 here that the 2PI Ward identity is incompatible with the corresponding
 1PI Ward identity is (to the author's knowledge) new and shows that this
 result is independent of the renormalisation scheme used.
 Here the 2PIEA for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{O}\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 scalar field theory is renormalised and solved in the Hartree-Fock approximatio
n at finite temperature, reproducing independently results known in the
 literature.
 The solution is then contrasted with the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

external propagator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 methods which have been advocated because they solve some of the phenomenologic
al problems, though not entirely satisfactorily.
 This sets the stage for the examination of symmetry improvement techniques
 in the remainder of the thesis.
\end_layout

