\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to derive correlation functions from the 2PIEA which do obey
 1PI style WIs.
 The idea is that one first computes the self-consistent, or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

internal,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 as solutions of the 2PI equations of motion, and then from these constructs
 a resummed 1PIEA whose functional derivatives are the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

external
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 propagators and vertices.
 This method is used frequently in the literature (see e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VanHees2002,Berges2005,Carrington2009"

\end_inset

) and was definitively studied by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VanHees2002"

\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma\left[\varphi\right]=\Gamma\left[\varphi,\Delta\left[\varphi\right]\right]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 is a solution of the 
\emph on
exact
\emph default
 2PI equations of motion, the natural definition of the resummed 1PIEA is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{\Gamma}\left[\varphi\right]=\tilde{\Gamma}\left[\varphi,\tilde{\Delta}\left[\varphi\right]\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Gamma}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
truncated
\emph default
 (not exact) 2PIEA and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Delta}\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 is a solution of the 
\emph on
truncated
\emph default
 equation of motion
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{\delta\tilde{\Gamma}\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\Delta}\right|_{\Delta=\tilde{\Delta}\left[\varphi\right]}=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is no longer equal to the exact 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The solution of the resummed 1PI equation of motion is the same as the
 truncated 2PI solution because
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta\tilde{\Gamma}\left[\varphi\right]}{\delta\varphi}=\left(\frac{\delta\tilde{\Gamma}\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\varphi}\right)_{\Delta=\tilde{\Delta}\left[\varphi\right]}+\frac{\delta\tilde{\Delta}\left[\varphi\right]}{\delta\varphi}\left(\frac{\delta\tilde{\Gamma}\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\Delta}\right)_{\Delta=\tilde{\Delta}\left[\varphi\right]}=\left(\frac{\delta\tilde{\Gamma}\left[\varphi,\Delta\right]}{\delta\varphi}\right)_{\Delta=\tilde{\Delta}\left[\varphi\right]},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

by the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Delta}\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, as long as the truncation of the 2PIEA is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{O}\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 invariant
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An example of a non-invariant truncation would be keeping the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{G}\Delta_{G}$
\end_inset

 term, and only that term, in the Hartree-Fock diagram.
 Any loop or large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 truncation will be automatically invariant.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Delta}\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 will transform as a symmetric rank-2 tensor and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Gamma}\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

 will be a scalar.
 Thus the derivation of the 1PI WIs carries through without modification
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\Gamma}\left[\varphi\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the external propagator, defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{\mathrm{ext}}^{-1}=\frac{\delta^{2}\tilde{\Gamma}\left[\varphi\right]}{\delta\varphi\delta\varphi},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

obeys the Goldstone theorem
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=\left(\Delta_{\mathrm{ext}}^{-1}\right)_{ab}T_{bc}^{A}\varphi_{c},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

as desired.
 Similarly defined higher order external vertices all obey the appropriate
 1PI type WIs.
 Clearly these definitions and properties can be extended also to higher
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

PIEA with minimal modification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This technique elegantly accomplishes its main aim: to define correlation
 functions satisfying 1PI WIs while including some effects of the 2PI resummatio
n in propagators.
 Unfortunately, there are several drawbacks to the method which may prompt
 one to consider alternative solutions to the problem of symmetries in 2PIEA.
 First, the method is not fully self-consistent in that the external propagators
 are not involved in the 2PI solution at all.
 The internal propagators appearing in the 2PI graphs are still unphysical
 and do not obey the 1PI WIs.
 As a result of unphysically massive Goldstone bosons in internal propagators,
 the external propagators are useless to predict decay rates, reaction threshold
s, absorptive parts of amplitudes, finite width effects and the unitarity
 of the theory is violated.
 Also an unphysical first order phase transition is still obtained in the
 Hartree-Fock approximation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "VanHees2002"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, the physical quantities (being represented by external rather
 than internal Green functions) are a further step removed from the underlying
 formalism of the theory.
 This greatly complicates the renormalisation procedure, which now requires
 the solution of non-linear coupled Bethe-Salpeter integral equations in
 order to find the renormalisation counter-terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Contrast to the Large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 method
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}{
\end_layout

