\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)=v$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\left(x\right)=\sigma$
\end_inset

 in the physical limit 
\begin_inset Formula $J=0$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(m^{2}+\sigma\right)v & =0,\\
\frac{i\hbar}{2}\int_{k}\frac{1}{k^{2}-\left(m^{2}+\sigma\right)} & =\frac{3}{g}\sigma-\frac{1}{2N}v^{2}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

In the broken phase the first equation gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=-m^{2}$
\end_inset

, and one recognises that after renormalisation the second equation is just
 the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 gap equation obtained previously for the Goldstone with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}=m^{2}+\sigma$
\end_inset

 as the Goldstone mass.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}-m^{2}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 above one indeed recovers the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 gap equation and the Goldstone theorem 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}v=0$
\end_inset

 in both phases.
 The advantage of this method via transformations of the functional integral
 rather than a direct expansion of the equations of motion is that the systemati
cs of the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 expansion are clearer.
 In particular, it is now obvious that the gap equations obtained are strictly
 valid to order 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1/N\right)$
\end_inset

 without having to worry about the combinatorics of higher order self-energy
 graphs.
 The disadvantage of this method is that the connection to the 2PIEA is
 less clear.
